<subSubSection id="C3276567FFFF5632B8B5FEF1FDE5FB4B" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8236ECFFFF5632B8B5FEF1FC08FC0B" blockId="6.[151,1127,323,1211]" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">
Living on a water surface enforces some strong ecological, physiological and behavioural constraints (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAC4B1DFFFF5632B941FED1FE5BFE8B" author="ANDERSEN N. M." box="[321,493,355,379]" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" refId="ref8370" refString="ANDERSEN N. M. 1982: The Semiaquatic Bugs (Hemiptera, Gerromorpha). Phylogeny, adaptations, biogeography, and classification. Entomonograph, vol. 3. Scandinavian Science Press, Klampenborg, 455 pp." type="book" year="1982">ANDERSEN 1982</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAC4B1DFFFF5632B9FAFED1FCA1FE8B" author="SPENCE J. R. &amp; ANDERSEN N. M." box="[506,791,355,379]" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" pagination="101 - 128" refId="ref10571" refString="SPENCE J. R. &amp; ANDERSEN N. M. 1994: Biology of water striders: interactions between systematics and ecology. Annual Review of Entomology 39: 101 - 128." type="journal article" year="1994">SPENCE &amp; ANDERSEN 1994</bibRefCitation>
). The comparison of the fossil 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632B897FE36FED8FE6B" authorityName="Andersen" authorityYear="1998" box="[151,366,388,411]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Limnoporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wilsoni">
<emphasis id="B949EAFEFFFF5632B897FE36FED8FE6B" box="[151,366,388,411]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">Limnoporus wilsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with extant congeners was used by to infer a ‘structural stasis’ in the group because the general habitus of fossil and extant specimens was practically inseparable 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAC4B1DFFFF5632B897FE71FE30FE2B" author="ANDERSEN N. M. &amp; SPENCE J. R. &amp; WILSON M. V. H." box="[151,390,451,475]" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" pagination="174 - 176" refId="ref8957" refString="ANDERSEN N. M., SPENCE J. R. &amp; WILSON M. V. H. 1993: 50 million years of structural stasis in water striders (Hemiptera, Gerridae). American Entomologist 39: 174 - 176." type="journal article" year="1993">ANDERSEN et al. (1993</bibRefCitation>
: Fig. 2). On the other hand, the adaptive shifts in habitats, for which gerromorphan bugs are so renowned, have ensured a rapid evolution of characters associated with locomotion, mating, feeding, and anti-predation strategies (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAC4B1DFFFF5632BB4BFDB1FC43FDEB" author="ANDERSEN N. M." box="[843,1013,515,539]" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" refId="ref8370" refString="ANDERSEN N. M. 1982: The Semiaquatic Bugs (Hemiptera, Gerromorpha). Phylogeny, adaptations, biogeography, and classification. Entomonograph, vol. 3. Scandinavian Science Press, Klampenborg, 455 pp." type="book" year="1982">ANDERSEN 1982</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAC4B1DFFFF5632BC00FDB1FE8AFDCB" author="SPENCE J. R. &amp; ANDERSEN N. M." pageId="6" pageNumber="257" pagination="101 - 128" refId="ref10571" refString="SPENCE J. R. &amp; ANDERSEN N. M. 1994: Biology of water striders: interactions between systematics and ecology. Annual Review of Entomology 39: 101 - 128." type="journal article" year="1994">SPENCE &amp; ANDERSEN 1994</bibRefCitation>
). The many constraints associated with life history adaptations in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BBD9FD91FBD0FDCB" baseAuthorityName="STYS &amp; KERZHNER" baseAuthorityYear="1975" box="[985,1126,547,571]" infraOrder="Gerromorpha" pageId="6" pageNumber="251" rank="infraOrder">Gerromorpha</taxonomicName>
have lead to numerous autapomorphies and convergences in morphological characters, which have complicated the interpretation of these traits in a phylogenetic context. The waterstriders have long been preferred organisms for comparisons of morphological and molecular characters in simultaneous analyses in order to make a reciprocal illumination of the molecular and morphological evidence. Most studies have addressed the three principal Holarctic water strider genera: 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632B93AFD56FD85FD0B" authority="Stal, 1868" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1868" box="[314,563,738,763]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Limnoporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B949EAFEFFFF5632B93AFD56FE0DFD0B" box="[314,443,740,763]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">Limnoporus</emphasis>
Stål, 1868
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BA3FFD56FCCEFD0B" authority="Schellenberg, 1800" authorityName="Schellenberg" authorityYear="1800" box="[575,888,739,763]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Aquarius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B949EAFEFFFF5632BA3FFD56FD17FD0B" box="[575,673,740,763]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">Aquarius</emphasis>
Schellenberg, 1800
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BBAFFD56FF7AFCEB" authority="Fabricius, 1794" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1794" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B949EAFEFFFF5632BBAFFD56FC43FD0B" box="[943,1013,740,763]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">Gerris</emphasis>
Fabricius, 1794
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAC4B1DFFFF5632B8D9FCB1FDB0FCEB" author="DAMGAARD J. &amp; COGNATO A. I." box="[217,518,771,795]" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" pagination="512 - 526" refId="ref9566" refString="DAMGAARD J. &amp; COGNATO A. I. 2003: Sources of character conflict in a clade of water striders (Heteroptera: Gerridae). Cladistics 19: 512 - 526." type="journal article" year="2003">DAMGAARD &amp; COGNATO 2003</bibRefCitation>
, 2005), but also sea skaters (
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BB2DFCB6FBE9FCEB" authority="Eschscholtz, 1822" authorityName="Eschscholtz" authorityYear="1822" box="[813,1119,771,795]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Halobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B949EAFEFFFF5632BB2DFCB6FC2CFCEB" box="[813,922,772,795]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">Halobates</emphasis>
Eschscholtz, 1822
</taxonomicName>
) have been studied (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAC4B1DFFFF5632B964FC91FDE5FCCB" author="DAMGAARD J. &amp; ANDERSEN N. M. &amp; CHENG L. &amp; SPERLING F. A. H." box="[356,595,803,827]" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" pagination="511 - 526" refId="ref9470" refString="DAMGAARD J., ANDERSEN N. M., CHENG L. &amp; SPERLING F. A. H. 2000: Phylogeny of sea skaters, Halobates (Hemiptera, Gerridae), based on mtDNA sequence and morphology. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 130: 511 - 526." type="journal article" year="2000">DAMGAARD et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Along with these investigations of more shallow relationships, a few studies have addressed relationships among families and subfamilies by including DNA sequence data (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAC4B1DFFFF5632B9E9FCD1FCB9FC8B" author="MURAJI M. &amp; TACHIKAWA S." box="[489,783,867,891]" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" pagination="615 - 626" refId="ref10080" refString="MURAJI M. &amp; TACHIKAWA S. 2000: Phylogenetic analysis of water striders (Hemiptera: Gerroidea) based on partial sequences of mitochondrial and nuclear ribosomol RNA genes. Entomological Science 3: 615 - 626." type="journal article" year="2000">MURAJI &amp; TACHIKAWA 2000</bibRefCitation>
, DAMGAARD et al. 2005). So far, DAMGAARD (in press) has presented the most inclusive study in terms of taxon and character sampling. A few subfamilies, such as Madeoveliinae (
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BAC8FC11FCEBFC4B" baseAuthorityName="ANDERSEN" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[712,861,931,955]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mesoveliidae</taxonomicName>
), Hyrcaninae (
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BBF4FC11FBEDFC4B" authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[1012,1115,931,955]" class="Insecta" family="Hebridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hebridae</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632B897FC71FEF6FC2B" authorityName="Villiers" authorityYear="1948" box="[151,320,963,987]" pageId="6" pageNumber="261" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Heterocleptinae">Heterocleptinae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632B973FC71FD94FC2B" authorityName="Esaki" authorityYear="1927" box="[371,546,963,987]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrometridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="261" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Limnobatodinae">Limnobatodinae</taxonomicName>
(both in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BA82FC71FC93FC2B" authorityName="Billberg" authorityYear="1820" box="[642,805,963,987]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrometridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hydrometridae</taxonomicName>
) still await inclusion, and will be very important for understanding the basal divergences of the infraorder.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8236ECFFFF5632B8B5FBB1FDE5FB4B" blockId="6.[151,1127,323,1211]" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">
<figureCitation id="13062A69FFFF5632B8B5FBB1FEBAFBEB" box="[181,268,1027,1051]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[113,144,1529,1548]" captionTargetBox="[119,1078,219,1497]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[113,1086,216,1497]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 1. Phylogenetic tree for the families of Gerromorpha and subfamilies of Hydrometridae, Veliidae and Gerridae summarized from DAMGAARD (in press). Temporal distribution of fossils indicated by heavy branches; unbroken branches denote range extensions inferred from fossils; broken branches denote range extension inferred from sister group relationships." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5340899" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5340899/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">Figure 1</figureCitation>
shows recognized gerromorphan fossils optimized onto the most parsimonious tree resulting from a simultaneous parsimony analysis of molecular and morphological characters by DAMGAARD (in press). The fossil gerrid subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BAD4FBF1FCD8FBAB" authorityName="Andersen &amp; Poinar" authorityYear="1992" box="[724,878,1091,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Electrobatinae">Electrobatinae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BBA4FBF6FF0AFB8B" authorityName="Perrichot, Nel &amp; Neraudeau" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Cretogerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albianus">
<emphasis id="B949EAFEFFFF5632BBA4FBF6FF0AFB8B" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">Cretogerris albianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has not been assigned to any subfamily, are placed unresolved at the base of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632B897FB31FF41FB6B" baseAuthorityName="PROKOP &amp; NEL" baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[151,247,1155,1179]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Gerridae</taxonomicName>
, and the two extant hydrometrid subfamilies, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BAD7FB31FC36FB6B" authorityName="Villiers" authorityYear="1948" box="[727,896,1155,1179]" pageId="6" pageNumber="261" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Heterocleptinae">Heterocleptinae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D6FFFFF5632BBB1FB31FBD5FB6B" authorityName="Esaki" authorityYear="1927" box="[945,1123,1155,1179]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrometridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="261" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Limnobatodinae">Limnobatodinae</taxonomicName>
, are placed according to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAC4B1DFFFF5632B994FB11FDF9FB4B" author="ANDERSEN N. M." box="[404,591,1187,1211]" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" refId="ref8370" refString="ANDERSEN N. M. 1982: The Semiaquatic Bugs (Hemiptera, Gerromorpha). Phylogeny, adaptations, biogeography, and classification. Entomonograph, vol. 3. Scandinavian Science Press, Klampenborg, 455 pp." type="book" year="1982">ANDERSEN (1982)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
